Multiple pieces of evidence indicate that NSAIDs, including ibuprofen, increase the risk of gastrointestinal bleeding and contribute to higher risks of hemorrhage due to their anticoagulant-like effects on platelet function. Although specific data on hip arthroplasty is limited, the general principle applies across surgeries involving high-risk bleed scenarios—especially since hip arthroplasty involves substantial soft tissue trauma and vascularity. Given that ibuprofen inhibits cyclooxygenase enzymes involved in platelet aggregation, its use perioperatively could theoretically exacerbate blood loss.

